\begin_layout Standard
A cumulative distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has the following properties:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq F(x)\leq1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty<x<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 This follows because 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a monotone increasing function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x_{1})\leq F(x_{2})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}\leq x_{2}$
\end_inset

 (think about the corresponding events ...).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{x\to-\infty}F(x)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{x\to\infty}F(x)=1$
\end_inset

.
 If the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has a finite image, then 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x)=0\mbox{ }(1)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 sufficiently small (large).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},\dots$
\end_inset

 the elements of the image 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has a positive jump equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{X}(x_{i})$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,\dots$
\end_inset

 and in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[x_{i},x_{i+1})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 has a constant value 
\begin_inset Formula $F(x_{i})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be shown that any function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 satisfying properties 1-4 is the distribution function of some discrete
 random variable!
